{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628534"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17222"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17222"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0.92,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9912"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56680"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1877"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23250"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening headache, fever, and neck pain. She has become increasingly confused over the past 24 hours. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and drowsy. Her observations are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETemperature: 38.5\u00b0C\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPulse rate: 110/min\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood pressure: 130/85 mmHg\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERespiratory rate: 22/min\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOxygen saturation: 97% on room air\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has marked neck stiffness and photophobia. While confused, she has no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most likely to explain these symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute glaucoma","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Viral encephalitis","Brain metastasis","Migraine with aura"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of central nervous system infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EViral encephalitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a combination of systemic symptoms (fever) and neurological manifestations (confusion, neck stiffness). The acute onset over three days with progressive confusion is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E causes severe eye pain and headache but does not cause fever, neck stiffness or confusion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral venous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause headache and altered mental status but typically does not cause fever or neck stiffness\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain metastasis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents more gradually and would be unlikely in a previously well person. Fever and neck stiffness are not typical features\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine with aura\u003C/strong\u003E may cause headache and photophobia but does not cause fever, neck stiffness or confusion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of fever, headache, confusion and neck stiffness should always raise concern for meningitis or encephalitis requiring urgent investigation and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fever, neck stiffness, and confusion are classic features of meningoencephalitis requiring urgent medical attention.","Viral encephalitis typically presents with a prodrome of systemic symptoms followed by neurological manifestations.","The combination of headache, fever, confusion and neck stiffness should prompt consideration of central nervous system infection."],"references":["Encephalitis. Paediatr Child Health. 1998 Jan;3(1):47-52. doi: 10.1093/pch/3.1.47. PMID: 20401198; PMCID: PMC2851264.","Ellul M, Solomon T. Acute encephalitis - diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2018 Mar;18(2):155-159. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.18-2-155. PMID: 29626021; PMCID: PMC6303463.","Ellul M, Solomon T. Acute encephalitis - diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2018 Mar;18(2):155-159. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.18-2-155. PMID: 29626021; PMCID: PMC6303463.","Alam AM, Easton A, Nicholson TR, Irani SR, Davies NWS, Solomon T, Michael BD. Encephalitis: diagnosis, management and recent advances in the field of encephalitides. Postgrad Med J. 2023 Jul 21;99(1174):815-825. doi: 10.1136/postgradmedj-2022-141812. Epub 2022 Jun 23. PMID: 37490360."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17222"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T19:55:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T19:56:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9912"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71